731131f-a.title: Celebrations - Parades - Municipal Events - Army Day Parade.
731131f-a.text:
Celebrations, Parades and Municipal Events
A set of three views of whct the writer believes to
be an Army Day Parade, being reviewed from a stand
at the Arsenal in Central Park. View No. 1 shows
the marchers passing the dfgnitaries which include
General Pershing (shown in close-up View 2). No. 3
is in a southward direction on Fifth Avenue and shows
Legonaires and Junior Units aprroaching the reviesing
stand. In this instance Sixty-third Street is to the
left and Central Park on the right.
About, 1925s

714145f-a.title: Manhattan: 63rd Street (East) - 5th Avenue
714145f-a.text:
No. 1 East 63rd Street, adjoining the N.E. corner of Fifth
Avenue, showing a 4 story brownstone residence. To the right is a
similar structure, No. 3, which is the property of Grace Wilson.
The 12 story apartment house on the left is No. 820 - Fifth Avenue
and is of particular interest because of its 18 room suites.
Occupants here in December 1937, included Alfred P. Sloan, Alfred
E. Smith, Mrs. Pierre Lorillard and Mrs. John Willys, according to
Albert B. Ashforth, Inc., agents for the Matchette Realty Corporation,
Owner8.
About 1933
